            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the Indiana income tax works</h2>
              <p>
                Indiana uses a <strong>flat state income tax rate</strong> plus
                an additional <strong>county income tax</strong> based on where
                you live or work. That means the same percentage applies to all
                of your taxable income, instead of progressive brackets.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Basic Indiana income tax formula
                </p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li><code>I</code> = Indiana taxable income</li>
                  <li>
                    <code>r<sub>state</sub></code> = state tax rate
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <code>r<sub>county</sub></code> = county tax rate
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Indiana state tax} = I \times r_{\text{state}} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{County income tax} = I \times r_{\text{county}} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Total Indiana income tax} = I \times
                  (r_{\text{state}} + r_{\text{county}}) \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Current Indiana state income tax rate</h3>
              <p>
                Indiana has been gradually reducing its flat state income tax
                rate. This calculator uses:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>2024 tax year:</strong> state rate ≈
                  <strong>3.05%</strong> (approximation based on recent
                  legislation)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>2023 tax year:</strong> state rate ≈
                  <strong>3.15%</strong>
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Because rates can change, always confirm the latest official
                rate with the
                <a href="https://www.in.gov/dor/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
                  >Indiana Department of Revenue</a
                >.
              </p>

              <h3>Indiana county income tax rates</h3>
              <p>
                Each county in Indiana can impose its own income tax, usually
                between about <strong>1%</strong> and <strong>3%</strong>. The
                exact rate depends on your:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>County of residence</strong> on January 1 of the tax
                  year, and
                </li>
                <li>Sometimes your <strong>county of employment</strong>.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator lets you enter your county rate manually so it
                stays accurate even if local rates change.
              </p>

              <h2>
                Step‑by‑step: how this calculator estimates your Indiana tax
              </h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Start with your Indiana taxable income.</strong> This
                  is your income after federal adjustments and deductions that
                  Indiana recognizes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Subtract pre‑tax deductions</strong> you enter
                  (401(k), HSA, etc.) to get the income base used in the
                  calculation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Apply the state rate</strong> for the selected tax
                  year to that income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Apply your county rate</strong> to the same income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Add state + county</strong> to get total Indiana
                  income tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you choose, the tool also
                  <strong>estimates federal income tax</strong> using a
                  simplified model and shows your approximate
                  <strong>after‑tax income</strong>.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Example calculation</h3>
              <p>Suppose you are single in 2024 with:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Indiana taxable income: <strong>$75,000</strong></li>
                <li>Pre‑tax deductions: <strong>$5,000</strong></li>
                <li>County rate: <strong>1.50%</strong></li>
              </ul>
              <p>Taxable base used by this tool:</p>
              <p>\[ I = 75{,}000 - 5{,}000 = 70{,}000 \]</p>
              <p>Indiana state tax (3.05%):</p>
              <p>\[ 70{,}000 \times 0.0305 = 2{,}135 \]</p>
              <p>County tax (1.50%):</p>
              <p>\[ 70{,}000 \times 0.015 = 1{,}050 \]</p>
              <p>Total Indiana income tax:</p>
              <p>\[ 2{,}135 + 1{,}050 = 3{,}185 \]</p>
              <p>Effective Indiana rate:</p>
              <p>\[ \frac{3{,}185}{75{,}000} \approx 4.25\% \]</p>

              <h2>Indiana income tax vs. federal income tax</h2>
              <p>
                Indiana’s flat tax is much simpler than the federal system. The
                federal government uses:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Progressive tax brackets</strong> that increase as
                  income rises
                </li>
                <li>
                  Different <strong>standard deductions</strong> by filing
                  status
                </li>
                <li>
                  Many <strong>credits and deductions</strong> (child tax
                  credit, education credits, etc.)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator includes a
                <strong>rough federal estimate</strong> to give you a quick
                sense of your total tax burden and take‑home pay, but it does
                not replace full tax software or professional advice.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about Indiana income tax</h2>

              <h3>Who has to file an Indiana state income tax return?</h3>
              <p>In general, you must file an Indiana return if:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You are an <strong>Indiana resident</strong> with income above
                  the filing threshold, or
                </li>
                <li>
                  You are a <strong>nonresident</strong> with Indiana‑source
                  income (for example, you work in Indiana).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Specific thresholds and rules change, so always check the latest
                guidance from the
                <a
                  href="https://www.in.gov/dor/i-am-a/individual/individual-income-tax-overview/"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener"
                  >Indiana Department of Revenue</a
                >.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I find my county income tax rate?</h3>
              <p>
                You can look up your current county rate on the Indiana DOR
                website or in their annual tax bulletins. Many payroll providers
                and tax software tools also list the correct rate based on your
                home address.
              </p>

              <h3>Does Indiana allow itemized deductions?</h3>
              <p>
                Indiana starts with your federal adjusted gross income and then
                applies specific
                <strong>add‑backs and deductions</strong> defined by state law.
                You do not itemize in the same way as on your federal return.
                This calculator assumes you are entering your
                <strong>Indiana taxable income</strong> after those adjustments.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this calculator accurate for filing my return?</h3>
              <p>
                This tool is designed for
                <strong>planning and education</strong>. It uses simplified
                formulas and may not capture every credit, deduction, or special
                situation. For filing, rely on official forms, approved tax
                software, or a qualified tax professional.
              </p>
